post_text:
üçéFREE BAGGED LUNCHES FOR CHILDREN AGES 0-18üçé

Beginning Monday, 3/23, St. John and Endicott Nutrition Services will be providing lunches during school closure!

Delivery of Lunches (via regular bus routes) or Pickup
Monday ‚Äì Thursday (11:00 ‚Äì 12:00)

Sign up by filling out the attached Google form or
call 509-648-3336 ext. 123 (St. John School) / 509-657-3523 ext. 107 (Endicott School)

IMPORTANT NOTES:

*This service is FREE to all children in the community ages 0-18 years.

*All children receiving a lunch must be present at delivery or pickup in order to receive a lunch.

*We need to know by Thursday each week if you plan on receiving the same amount of meals the following week in order for us to plan for the correct amount food.

*If you are aware of any families in the community that do not have children going to our school that would benefit, please let us know their name(s)/phone number(s) in the comment section or share this form with them.

Thank you!

The Cooperative Schools of Endicott and St. John have been chosen to participate in the Silverwood Read 2 Ride Program this year for grades preschool-sixth grade!

Reading Logs will be sent home with students by the end of this week.

Forms due back on March 31, 2020.

Students can count the time they read to themselves, to someone else or having someone read to them. (Homework and school assignments do not count.)

If you have any questions, Julie Lust at Endicott School is the coordinator for both districts. You can reach her at 648-9942, 657-3523 or email her at jlust@sjeschools.org.

post_text:
Saturday, February 8th, the St. John-Endicott FFA welcomes 12 schools to our local gun club to hold our annual SJE FFA Trap Shoot! It was a full day of fun and excitement as some of the best shooters in the state came together to compete.

Our own Ryan Willson came out as the Highest Individual Shooter with a score of 47 out of 50! Cale Crider came close to placing 5th High Individual with a score of 41 but lost out in a 3 way shoot out for 5th place.

The top three teams were:
Kettle Falls FFA
St. John - Endicott FFA
Pine City Malden Youth Trap Club

We would like to thank all of the schools that came out to support our chapter and spend the day in St. John!

post_text: ‚ÄúThis week the SJE FFA Conduct of Chapter Meetings team attended the ‚ÄúSuper Bowl of LDEs‚Äù Clinic hosted by Asotin FFA. The team consists of freshmen Kyra Holt, Jacob Swannack, Bailey Brown, Olivia Kjack, Brennen Gonzalez, and Gabe Morgan. After a morning of workshops, they put their skills to a test in a practice presentation. Out of the seven CCM teams that participated, SJE FFA was awarded a gavel for being the hardest working team at the event. Our members were invested in the workshops and asked important questions. They came in with a positive attitude and it did not go unnoticed! We are proud of these freshmen for their commitment to the team and to getting better everyday!‚Äù

üíØü¶Ö St. John Elementary First Graders celebrated our 100th Day of School one day early! (We were determine to not let our unexpected snow day on Wednesday alter our celebration and countdown!)

Together we read 100 books, solved 100 math equations, wrote about what life might be like when we are 100 years old, and enjoyed matching each other in our new shirts! Our favorite activities included: Science Experiment - ‚ÄúDoes it take 100 licks to get to the center of a Tootsie Pop?‚Äù and STEM Challenge - ‚ÄúWho can build the tallest tower using 100 marshmallows and 100 toothpicks?‚Äù

What a wonderful way to end our week. The first graders are truly ‚Äú ONE HUNDRED DAYS BRIGHTER‚Äù!

St. John-Endicott School District added 6 new photos from November 14, 2019 at 1:45 PM.
November 14, 2019 at 2:51 PM ¬∑

Today a few students represented our school and the SJE FFA Chapter at the State FFA Potato Evaluation Contest. Our students dove right into learning the ins and outs of grading potatoes and their hard work paid off!

Out of the 35 teams that competed, SJE secured 13th place. Our members graded 100 potatoes according to U.S. grading standards, identified various potato blemishes and diseases, ranked plates of seed potatoes according to grading standards and gave oral reasons on the placing of ten potatoes.

Out of the 153 students that competed today, our members placed in the following ranks:
Kyra Holt - 40th
Olivia Kjack - 55th
Wyatt Walker - 60th
Keely Jones - 65th
Brooklyn Bailey - 86th
Cale Crider - 91st
Dakota Jones - 99th

The SJE FFA looks forward to improving their skills for next year and hope to continue representing our communities with pride at many state events to come!

LaCrosse Schools
October 21, 2019 at 5:29 PM ¬∑

The SJEL high school boys basketball team will be having a workday on Saturday, October 26th. The workday will begin @ 8AM in SJ. We will meet in the parking lot between the football field and the gym. This workday is our fundraiser for the team. Our goal is to raise enough money to buy team polo shirts for away games and hopefully have enough left over to build our savings for future years. We will be doing odd jobs, yard clean-ups, sweeping, hauling leaves - just about anything short of home renovation. We will start in SJ and work our way thru Endicott to LaCrosse during the day, depending on the jobs that have been prearranged. Please have your boys come prepared to work. While this is a fundraiser, it is also a TEAM activity. Please have the boys bring brooms, shovels, pitchforks, garbage cans, gloves, lunch, plenty of hydration fluids and a good attitude. Please, direct questions about this event to Coach Stubbs via email or cell phone(509-595-3329) or Ken Gering at the SJ bus garage (509-648-3402).

Last night, September 23rd, most of the students from the Agriculture Mechanics class attended the city council meeting to pitch their prototypes for safety flag holders to be installed at various busy intersections in town.

They prepared a informational pamphlet and two different types of flag holders to give the city choices to move forward with.

Our goal is to build and install these flag holders by October 31, 2019 (Halloween) so that our many trick-or-treaters will be visible and SAFE during their night time activities.

The students have taken ownership of this project and we are so proud of the work they have done and will continue to do in our community!

The students who have participated in this project are: Roxy, Cale, Jakob, Wyatt, Matthew,
Alex, Connor, Brady and Trae

Although our FFA chapter has not been together this spring, our next team of officers has been elected in preparation for the coming school year! Officer candidates were asked to complete a written application to explain why they wanted to serve as an officer and what ideas they want to bring to our chapter. Then, our chapter members voted for the members they wanted to lead our chapter through the 2020 - 2021 school year.

Serving as an officer is an excellent opportunity to serve not only our FFA chapter but the school and comunity at large. These six young leaders have shown their commitment to FFA over the past year through their participation in CDE's (Career Development Events) and SAE‚Ä¶

St. John-Endicott School District is at St. John/Endicott High School.
March 8, 2019 at 9:22 AM ¬∑ Saint John, WA ¬∑

Our 2019 FFA Parliamentary Procedure team! They have been practicing in the mornings before school for the last few weeks to prepare for their first competition on the 12th.

The contest requires teams to conduct a mock meeting in which students must follow the proper parliamentary procedures to complete business that has been presented to them. Parliamentary procedure takes lots of practice and studying to become familiar with all of the rules. These students have been working as a team for two years.

On Tuesday, they will head to Colton to compete against four other schools in District 6 FFA to earn a spot in the district competition that will happen later this month.

post_text:
The audition for the Missoula Children's Theatre production of Blackbeard the Pirate will be held on Monday, March 25, 2019 at 3:00pm in the St. John Elementary School Gym.

Bus transportation will be provided for Endicott students. This bus is scheduled to leave the Endicott School at 2:30pm. There are roles for St. John and Endicott students Kindergarten through 8th Grade. Approximately 50-60 students will be cast to appear in the show with the MCT Tour Actors/Directors. There is no guarantee that everyone who auditions will be cast in the play. This is a group audition - no advance preparation is necessary, but a smile J never hurts. Students should just be ready to come and have a good time!

If your child is interest in participating in auditions, please look in your child‚Äôs backpacks for the permission slips sent home 2/25! They need to return to school no later than Monday, March 11th to participate!

ATTENTION PARENTS/GUARDIANS/STAFF:

Thank you for your feedback regarding yesterday's test alert message!

After speaking with the technical team at School Messenger, we realized we didn't have the system configured to send our alert to all forms of contact for all of our parents/guardians/staff yesterday.

We have corrected the configuration and going forward all messages, aside from attendance and food service notifications, will go to all forms of contact we have for all of our parents/guardians/staff.

If you haven't already opted in for text alerts and would like to do so, a text message will be sent today at approximately 4:00pm asking you to reply Yes or Y in order to opt in.

Thanks again for your patience as we work through the configuration of our new alert system!

November 30, 2018 ¬∑ Saint John, WA ¬∑

St. John Stock Show 2019

Jill Swannack was kind enough to bring in five feeder lambs and five goats to the fair this year so that students would have the opportunity to show an animal. Students who participated are Logan Stanley, Rylie Lamb, Owen Swannack, Cale Crider, Roxy Dickerson, and Keely Jones.

This morning the students came in and washed and prepared their animals for show.

Roxy received Grand Champion Sheep Showman and Rylie was awarded Reserve Champion Sheep Showman. Owen won Grand Champion Goat Showman and Logan came in as Reserve Champion Goat Showman.

This has been a wonderful experience for all of the students involved and we can't wait for next year!

POSITION: 4/5 LONG-TERM SUBSTITUTE TEACHER
(Multi-age Classroom)

CONTRACT LENGTH: Start Approximately December 3, 2018 through March 29, 2019
8:00 AM - 3:45 PM (Monday-Friday)

LOCATION: ENDICOTT SCHOOL DISTRICT
308 School Drive
Endicott, WA 99125

MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS:
‚Ä¢ A valid Washington State Teaching Certificate with an endorsement in Elementary Education

APPLICATION PROCEDURE:
The following materials must be submitted to the Endicott School District, 308 School Drive, Endicott, WA 99125. Please visit our web site at www.sje.wednet.edu for certificated job application. All questions or inquiries can be directed to Bruce Porubek at 509-657-3523. Applications must be received by November 6, 2018.

1. Letter of Application
2. District Certificated Application Form
3. Personal Resume
4. Three current Letters of Recommendation
5. Transcripts (unofficial are fine; official copies will be required if hired for position)
6. Copy of Washington State Teaching Certificate or evidence of eligibility

Endicott School Board Appointment
At-Large Position
Applications are being accepted through 12:00 pm noon Wednesday, August 22, 2018 for an opening on the Endicott School Board. Interviews will be conducted at the regularly scheduled board meeting on Monday, August 27, 2018. The vacancy occurs in the Director District #2 which is an At-Large position and is open to any qualified applicant living within the Endicott School District boundary. For official boundary information, please contact the School District. Applications are available at the School District by contacting Dana Crider, 308 School Drive, Endicott, WA 99125 or call 509-657-3523.

Thank you SJEL Football players for representing your communities at Whitworth these past three days. Your hard work and dedication will definitely pay off this Fall.
